{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":10091,"record_hash":"sha256:1652b454f85732ec41ba0cfcffdc62926d207f8ce991d2c6fafdaa780c472a5c","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:46:50.250Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"{\"previous_status\":{\"completed\":\"Mostly yes, but only if `sessions` and `timeline` expose **why this evidence is attached** and **how muddy it is**. Without that, the tools create false confidence by making weak matches look like curated history.\\n\\nKeep the toolset, but make `sessions` return small provenance fields:\\n\\n```text\\nsession_key\\nstarted_at / ended_at\\nlast_turn_at\\nmatched_by: branch_observed | review_observed | change_observed | explicit_reference | workspace_path | commit_touched\\nobserved_branches: [name@turns]\\nprimary_branch: name | null\\nbranch_switches: count\\nturn_count\\nrecord_count\\nlatest_summary: optional short human/agent summary\\n```\\n\\nThe big one is `matched_by`. An agent needs to know “this session touched the branch” versus “this session merely had the branch visible nearby.” That is evidence, not scoring.\\n\\nFor `timeline`, expose per-turn context, not just events:\\n\\n```text\\nturn_key\\nindex\\ntimestamp\\nactor: user | agent | tool\\nobserved_branches\\nactive_branch: name | null\\nbranch_changed: true/false\\nreferenced_reviews / referenced_changes\\ncommands_or_tools: compact list\\nsummary: one-line if available\\nrecord_count\\n```\\n\\nAlso include a session-level header before the turns:\\n\\n```text\\nsession_key\\nquery_context: branch foo\\nmatched_by: branch_observed\\nobserved_branches: foo, bar, baz\\nbranch_switches: 4\\ncoverage: turns 12-31 of 88 shown\\n```\\n\\nThat last `coverage` bit matters. If I’m seeing the last 20 turns of an 88-turn session, I should not act like I understand the whole thing.\\n\\nI would avoid “confidence: high/medium/low”. That gets product-y fast and agents will over-trust it. Prefer raw ambiguity signals:\\n\\n- matched by what\\n- which branches were observed\\n- whether multiple branches appeared in the same session\\n- whether the requested branch was active or just present\\n- how much of the session is shown\\n- whether there are gaps or truncation\\n- timestamps, so stale evidence looks stale\\n\\nOne small addition I’d seriously consider: `sessions --explain-match`.\\n\\nNot a separate scoring system, just a terse reason:\\n\\n```text\\nMatched because branch `foo` was observed in turns 18, 19, and 27.\\nOther observed branches: `main`, `bar`.\\nNo explicit user reference to `foo` found.\\n```\\n\\nThat is exactly the kind of thing a receiving agent needs to avoid making shit up with a straight face.\"}}","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:46:50.250Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}